<seg id=1> Two South Korean Soldiers Captured during the Korean War Escape From North Korea after 45 Years in Jail </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Reuters, Seoul, Telegram) The South Korean State Security Planning Bureau said the day before yesterday that two South Korean soldiers on the Korean War death list recently escaped from North Korea.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> According to the statement issued by the State Security Planning Bureau, 67-year-old Jin Fuji and 71-year-old Pu Dongyi (names are transliterations) returned to South Korea recently via a third country.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The statement said that the two persons were captured by Chinese soldiers in the northeast region near the North-South Korean border during the Korean War.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The statement says that they were forced to provide slave labor in North Korean coal mines before their escape. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> At the end of the 1950-1953 Korean War, the South Korean Ministry of Defense put tens of thousands of missing soldiers on a death list. Jin Fuji and Pu Dongyi are two of them.  </seg>
<seg id=7> The final agreement signed by South Korea and North Korea is a cease-fire agreement, not a formal peace treaty.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Technically, South Korea and North Korea are still at war.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The two men unexpectedly became relatives by marriage during the jail period.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> According to the statement, Jin Fuji's second son, Jin Ningqiu, married Pu Dongyi's fourth daughter, Pu Zhengxin, in April, 1991. </seg>
<seg id=11> The statement did not explain further.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> An officer from the State Security Planning Bureau said that Jin Fuji and Pu Dongyi are currently being detained for questioning by the authorities.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> The National Defense Department once stated that about 20,000 soldiers went missing during the Korean War. The Department thinks that there are still some survivors.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=14> An escaped prisoner of war said in April that as far as he knows, there are still 50-60 South Korean soldiers currently jailed in North Korea.  </seg>
</p>
